	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				A few verifiable corrections to the above, from someone who has read every volume of available lore and requested every bit of advice from existing master fletchers on this bow: first, it does take only two micro servos to attempt to make a Trueshot. One to combine in the materials bag given to you by Maesyn Trueshot in the Kelethin ranger guild when you tell him &quot;I am willing to gather the materials for the trueshot.&quot; Combine one micro servo, one spool of dwarven wire, one shard of Treant wood, and one spiderling silk in the bag, (meaning put the items in, then press the Combine button), hand it to Maesyn, and he will return to you the Treant bow staff, a Lore item.<BR>
<BR>
Where to find the four components:<BR>
Micro servos: in Steamfont, can be found on runaway clockworks and rogue clockworks. These mobs look exactly like spiderlings from a distance, so track them, and inspect to save time. Runaways are very weak, green at about level 7 or 8. Rogues range from about 9 to 13. The servos don't drop commonly, and the clockworks are fairly common, but over a wide territory. Luckily, the only people truly dedicated to this quest are likely to be rangers, as it is not a cost-effective endeavour, and will not return much experience at all after level 14 or 15, and rangers have the ability to track the little tin buggers.<BR>
<BR>
Be super careful, some areas frequented by clockworks are also thick with skeletons, large plague rats, minotaur slavers, harpies, earth elementals, and other ultraviolent nasties. They all like to train, so keep hitting 'track' from time to time to see what and how many are in your area.<BR>
<BR>
The treant shards you can get from a Ranger named Jyle Windshot, who can be found in Freeport. Some sick SOB decided that there should be TWO Jyle Windshots in town, which has led to endless bickering and ignorant assumptions by so many newbies. The WRONG one (for this quest, at least)of them is in the Inn immediately to your left from the dock after arriving from Butcherblock. When you hail him, he will say, &quot;I see you enjoy barging in to people's rooms unannounced!&quot; or similar. Ask him about the Treant Shards and he will ask you for a Faydark Champion's tunic, which is not all that easy to get, especially since you need MANY treant shards for your Trueshot attempts. Give him the finger and head to West Freeport.<BR>
<BR>
The real Jyle is in the Hogcaller's Inn in West Freeport. Again, track makes this much easier. Also, people like to whack him (God knows why), so you might need to wait upstairs for him to spawn. He will be much more friendly when you hail him, his clothing is a little lighter brown, and he even looks cuter. When asked about Treant Shards, this Jyle doesn't say a whole lot, (sorry, no quote), but you just need to hand him one Small Lantern at a time, and he will give you one piece of 'wooden shards', which are the Treant wood, and thank you profusely. He will also give you a Treant Heart from time to time, which is Lore, No Drop, and is used in making the Raincaller bow, something you will not be even contemplating until level 40+. Get a whole pile of treant wood, then head for the docks again.<BR>
<BR>
Take the ship to butcherblock, but get off at the first stop, Sisters Island. There is a merchant in one of the first huts off the dock, slightly right of dead ahead, who sells kiola nuts. They cost around 1 gp, and you need lots. Get lots. Don't spend too much time on this island, ie, catch the very next ship out of there, because there are occasionally pirates and brigands that will kill you on sight.<BR>
<BR>
Take the boat to Butcherblock and head for Kaladim. You will need as many flasks of water as you have Kiola nuts, and the only place I could find in Kaladim is in the northernmost part of the city, in front of the paladin's guild. If you don't mind seeing LOADING, PLEASE WAIT in red on your screen for more lines than there is dialogue, buy the water in advance at Freeport, Sisters Isle, or Kelethin.<BR>
<BR>
Find Irontoe's Eats in South Kaladim, a dark green building to the left after the main city gates. Give Tumpy Irontoe one Kiola nut and one flask of water, and he will give you one Tumpy Tonic. You need 2 Tumpy Tonics per dwarven wire. This is why you needed so many stupid Kiola nuts.<BR>
<BR>
Take the Tumpy Tonics to Trantor Everhot, also in South Kaladim, but on the right side as you enter the city gates. He will either be in his home, or in his forge, so track him down. Give him two Tumpy Tonics, he gives you one Dwarven Wire.<BR>
<BR>
Spiderling silks cost about 2sp from a merchant, but are very easy to get from widow hatchlings and their corpses lying in the Kelethin newbie hunting zone.<BR>
<BR>
After you give the four combined items to Maesyn in the materials pack he gives you, and get the Treant Bowstaff, the master fletching part comes in. To fletch the Trueshot, you need the bowstaff, another dwarven wire, and another micro servo, as well as a planing tool (about 12-13pp from Kelethin bowyer merchant Sylne or similar). I won't even talk about learning fletching, Everlore has a good guide on that, so does Allakhazam's on the links page. Bottom line is you have to be VERY good to have good chances of succeeding.<BR>
<BR>
Yes, people have attempted it at lower levels of skill, and succeeded, and yes, masters have attempted, and failed, numerous times in a row. No, the quest is not buggy, and no, Verant is not being unreasonably stringent in this. Maesyn comes right out and says, &quot;Even a master fletcher will fail from time to time.&quot; There are different levels of mastery, of course, and just because you reach skill level 100 and your skills sheet says 'Master' next to Fletching, does not mean you can make any bow or arrow with 100% success.<BR>
<BR>
The skill caps out at 200, and dig this: *even people at 200 fail at this bow*. From what I've gathered, a lifetime success rate of 3 out of 5 is not unreasonable for fletchers *after reaching 190 or above*. People at 150 have failed 20 times in a row, people at 85 have succeeded on their first try. You wisdom also comes into play in your success rate.<BR>
<BR>
People misunderstand the way probability works. If something has a 60% chance of success, many people think, &quot;Cool. If I make 10 attempts, I should be able to make 6 before I fail once.&quot; More likely, you could fail 4 times in a row, then have a success.<BR>
<BR>
And yes, if you are a powerleveller, or a money horder, this 'quest sucks.' It takes a lot of time, gets you very little money and almost no experience as a result. To get your fletching skill to 200 alone could cost 1000 to 1500pp, easy. Bottom line: this is a roleplaying quest. This quest is for rangers dedicated enough to their guild and to their natural gifts of archery and fletching to craft the finest bow available that is unique to them. It is a source of pride for a ranger to wield her own handmade Trueshot, a feeling that transcends gaining the next level, or making a 200pp profit. It's not for everyone.<BR>
<BR>
Regards,<BR>
Kyona E.<BR>
Ranger of Faydark for the Fifteenth Season<BR>
[Innoruuk]<BR>
<BR>
Please email me at my brother's address above if you have any questions, comments, flames, or praises for me, or give me a /tell sometime.  
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
